1
00:02:13,427 --> 00:02:14,428
Stop now.

2
00:02:15,345 --> 00:02:17,055
Tell me where it is.

3
00:02:22,269 --> 00:02:26,565
You and your brethren possess
what is not rightfully yours.

4
00:02:27,357 --> 00:02:31,069
I don't know what you are talking about.

5
00:02:31,445 --> 00:02:34,114
Is it a secret you will die for?

6
00:02:35,115 --> 00:02:37,159
- Please.
- As you wish.

7
00:02:38,035 --> 00:02:39,411
Wait!

8
00:02:43,415 --> 00:02:45,584
My God, forgive me.

9
00:02:47,169 --> 00:02:49,212
In the sacristy,

10
00:02:49,671 --> 00:02:53,133
the church of Saint-Sulpice,
is the Rose Line.

11
00:02:53,216 --> 00:02:55,135
Beneath the Rose.

12
00:02:57,596 --> 00:02:58,972
Thank you.

13
00:03:33,006 --> 00:03:34,132
Thank you.

14
00:03:35,133 --> 00:03:36,134
Thank you.

15
00:03:47,270 --> 00:03:52,234
Symbols are a language
that can help us understand our past.

16
00:03:52,776 --> 00:03:56,947
As the saying goes,
a picture says a thousand words,

17
00:03:57,030 --> 00:04:00,033
but which words?

18
00:04:01,076 --> 00:04:04,746
Interpret for me, please, this symbol.
First thing that comes to mind. Anybody?

19
00:04:04,830 --> 00:04:07,165
- Hatred, racism.
- Ku Klux Klan.

20
00:04:07,290 --> 00:04:12,671
Yes, yes, interesting.
But they would disagree with you in Spain.

21
00:04:12,796 --> 00:04:16,091
There, they are robes worn by priests.

22
00:04:16,550 --> 00:04:18,677
Now this symbol. Anyone?

23
00:04:18,885 --> 00:04:19,886
Evil.

24
00:04:21,138 --> 00:04:22,389
In English, please.

25
00:04:22,514 --> 00:04:23,723
Devil's pitchfork.

26
00:04:23,807 --> 00:04:26,017
Poor, poor Poseidon.

27
00:04:26,643 --> 00:04:28,311
That is his trident.

28
00:04:28,395 --> 00:04:32,190
A symbol of power
to millions of the ancients.

29
00:04:32,274 --> 00:04:33,442
Now this symbol.

30
00:04:34,109 --> 00:04:36,653
- Madonna and child.
- Faith. Christianity.

31
00:04:36,778 --> 00:04:40,365
No. No, it's the pagan god Horus
and his mother Isis

32
00:04:40,449 --> 00:04:43,410
centuries before the birth of Christ.

33
00:04:43,493 --> 00:04:47,289
Understanding our past determines actively

34
00:04:47,372 --> 00:04:50,584
our ability to understand the present.

35
00:04:50,667 --> 00:04:54,838
So how do we sift truth from belief?

36
00:04:55,547 --> 00:04:58,884
How do we write our own histories,
personally or culturally,

37
00:04:58,967 --> 00:05:01,136
and thereby define ourselves?

38
00:05:01,219 --> 00:05:06,016
How do we penetrate years, centuries,
of historical distortion

39
00:05:06,099 --> 00:05:09,227
to find original truth?

40
00:05:09,394 --> 00:05:12,731
Tonight, this will be our quest.

41
00:05:12,856 --> 00:05:15,859
My son is a student of yours at Harvard.

42
00:05:15,942 --> 00:05:18,320
- Michael Culp? He adores you.
- Yeah.

43
00:05:18,403 --> 00:05:20,489
He says you're the best teacher
he's ever had.

44
00:05:20,572 --> 00:05:24,367
Ms. Culp, I think I already gave
Michael an A-minus.

45
00:05:24,910 --> 00:05:26,369
He told me. Thank you.

46
00:05:26,453 --> 00:05:27,913
Mr. Langdon?

47
00:05:28,455 --> 00:05:29,915
Hi.

48
00:05:29,998 --> 00:05:31,416
Bonjour, Professor.

49
00:05:32,250 --> 00:05:37,422
I'm Lieutenant Collet from DCPJ.
A kind of French FBI.

50
00:05:38,089 --> 00:05:40,759
Will you take a look at this photo, please?

51
00:05:40,842 --> 00:05:43,845
My police chief, Captain Fache, had hoped,

52
00:05:43,929 --> 00:05:47,349
considering your expertise
and the markings on the body,

53
00:05:47,432 --> 00:05:48,934
you might assist us.

54
00:05:57,859 --> 00:05:59,694
Will you excuse me a moment?

55
00:06:03,240 --> 00:06:05,200
I was supposed to have drinks with him
earlier this evening.

56
00:06:05,283 --> 00:06:06,451
Yes, we know.

57
00:06:07,786 --> 00:06:09,955
We found your name in his daily planner.

58
00:06:11,122 --> 00:06:13,875
He never showed. I waited for over an hour.

59
00:06:17,128 --> 00:06:19,798
Why would someone do this to him?

60
00:06:19,965 --> 00:06:22,551
You misunderstand, Professor.

61
00:06:23,468 --> 00:06:25,720
He was shot, yes.

62
00:06:25,804 --> 00:06:28,557
But what you see in the photograph,

63
00:06:28,640 --> 00:06:31,101
Monsieur Saunière did to himself.

64
00:06:34,312 --> 00:06:38,650
Teacher, all four are dead.

65
00:06:39,484 --> 00:06:42,571
The sénéchaux and the Grand Master himself.

66
00:06:42,737 --> 00:06:45,824
Then I assume you have the location.

67
00:06:45,991 --> 00:06:49,119
Confirmed by all.

68
00:06:49,286 --> 00:06:51,705
Independently.

69
00:06:52,497 --> 00:06:56,835
I had feared the Priory's penchant
for secrecy might prevail.

70
00:07:00,338 --> 00:07:04,467
The prospect of death is strong motivation.

71
00:07:07,887 --> 00:07:10,307
It is here.

72
00:07:10,557 --> 00:07:13,018
In Paris, Teacher.

73
00:07:13,935 --> 00:07:19,399
It hides beneath the Rose in Saint-Sulpice.

74
00:07:19,899 --> 00:07:22,652
You will go forth, Silas.

75
00:08:35,600 --> 00:08:39,104
I chastise my body.

76
00:09:16,850 --> 00:09:18,977
Captain Fache is waiting for you.

77
00:09:27,318 --> 00:09:28,611
Okay.

78
00:09:39,914 --> 00:09:41,332
- Mr. Langdon.
- Yes.

79
00:09:41,875 --> 00:09:43,793
I'm Captain Bezu Fache.

80
00:09:44,836 --> 00:09:46,337
You like our pyramid?

81
00:09:46,421 --> 00:09:47,505
It's magnificent.

82
00:09:48,339 --> 00:09:50,216
A scar on the face of Paris.

83
00:09:51,384 --> 00:09:53,178
After me, please.

84
00:10:00,894 --> 00:10:03,021
It's the pairing of those two pyramids.

85
00:10:03,521 --> 00:10:04,939
It's unique.

86
00:10:05,023 --> 00:10:07,192
The two are geometric echoes.

87
00:10:07,358 --> 00:10:08,359
Fascinating.

88
00:10:11,070 --> 00:10:14,616
I'm not sure how much help
I'm gonna be here this evening.

89
00:10:15,325 --> 00:10:17,952
How well did you know the curator?

90
00:10:18,036 --> 00:10:19,329
Not very well.

91
00:10:19,412 --> 00:10:22,999
Frankly, I was surprised
when he contacted me.

92
00:10:31,049 --> 00:10:33,426
Could we take the stairs?

93
00:10:48,024 --> 00:10:51,402
So Saunière requested tonight's meeting.

94
00:10:51,486 --> 00:10:52,612
Yes.

95
00:10:52,821 --> 00:10:54,280
How? Did he call you?

96
00:10:55,949 --> 00:10:59,202
E-mail. He heard I was in Paris.

97
00:11:00,495 --> 00:11:03,456
- Had something to discuss.
- What?

98
00:11:08,419 --> 00:11:11,214
You seem uncomfortable.

99
00:11:22,892 --> 00:11:27,063
The Grande Galerie.
This is where you found the body.

100
00:11:27,146 --> 00:11:28,940
How would you know that?

101
00:11:29,941 --> 00:11:33,027
I recognize the parquet floor
from the Polaroid.

102
00:11:33,111 --> 00:11:34,654
It's unmistakable.

103
00:11:43,997 --> 00:11:45,290
Dear God.

104
00:11:49,294 --> 00:11:51,671
Let's cover the talking points again,
Your Eminence.

105
00:11:51,754 --> 00:11:54,841
Many call Opus Dei a brainwashing cult.

106
00:11:54,966 --> 00:11:57,677
Others, an ultraconservative
Christian secret society.

107
00:11:57,760 --> 00:12:00,221
Obviously, some people fear
what they don't understand.

108
00:12:00,305 --> 00:12:02,724
Perhaps a less defensive
tack, Your Eminence.

109
00:12:02,807 --> 00:12:04,934
The press continue to be harsh with us.

110
00:12:06,769 --> 00:12:10,690
We are not Cafeteria Catholics.

111
00:12:11,149 --> 00:12:13,318
We don't pick and choose
which rules to follow.

112
00:12:13,401 --> 00:12:16,029
We follow doctrine. Rigorously.

113
00:12:16,821 --> 00:12:20,909
Does doctrine necessarily include
vows of chastity, tithing,

114
00:12:20,992 --> 00:12:24,120
and atonement for sins
through self-flagellation and the cilice?

115
00:12:24,495 --> 00:12:28,625
Many of our followers are married.
Many of them have families.

116
00:12:28,833 --> 00:12:31,669
Only a small proportion
choose to live ascetic lives.

117
00:12:31,878 --> 00:12:34,839
- Why are some media...
- That will be all, Michael, thank you.

118
00:12:35,381 --> 00:12:36,591
Aringarosa.

119
00:12:37,842 --> 00:12:41,512
Silas has succeeded. The legend is true.

120
00:12:41,846 --> 00:12:43,723
It hides beneath the Rose.

121
00:12:44,015 --> 00:12:47,060
My part of our bargain is nearly fulfilled.

122
00:12:47,602 --> 00:12:50,688
I meet the council in an hour.

123
00:12:50,939 --> 00:12:54,692
I will have your money tonight, Teacher.

124
00:12:55,026 --> 00:12:57,487
The Vitruvian Man.

125
00:12:57,570 --> 00:13:00,198
It's one of Leonardo da Vinci's
most famous sketches.

126
00:13:00,907 --> 00:13:02,867
And the star on his skin?

127
00:13:03,701 --> 00:13:06,037
- A pentacle.
- And its meaning?

128
00:13:06,454 --> 00:13:08,539
The pentacle is a pagan religious icon.

129
00:13:09,123 --> 00:13:10,792
Devil worship.

130
00:13:10,875 --> 00:13:15,213
No. No, no, no. The pentacle before that.

131
00:13:16,047 --> 00:13:18,424
This is a symbol for Venus.

132
00:13:19,175 --> 00:13:21,511
It represents the female
half of all things.

133
00:13:21,594 --> 00:13:24,555
You are telling me
that Saunière's last act on earth

134
00:13:24,639 --> 00:13:28,726
was to draw a goddess symbol
on his chest? Why?

135
00:13:30,186 --> 00:13:33,439
Captain Fache,
obviously I can't tell you why.

136
00:13:34,357 --> 00:13:38,611
I can tell you he, as well as anyone,
knows the meaning of this symbol,

137
00:13:38,695 --> 00:13:40,989
and it has nothing to do
with worshiping the devil.

138
00:13:41,072 --> 00:13:42,573
- Is that so?
- Yes.

139
00:13:42,657 --> 00:13:46,869
Then what do you make of this?

140
00:13:47,453 --> 00:13:51,416
"O, Draconian devil. Oh, lame saint."

141
00:13:51,916 --> 00:13:54,752
It's a phrase.
Doesn't mean anything, not to me.

142
00:13:55,420 --> 00:13:59,007
What would you do if you had
such limited time to send a message?

143
00:14:00,466 --> 00:14:05,054
Well, I suppose I'd try
to identify my killer.

144
00:14:05,930 --> 00:14:07,056
Precisely.

145
00:14:07,765 --> 00:14:09,392
Precisely.

146
00:14:09,475 --> 00:14:10,601
So, Professor...

147
00:14:12,145 --> 00:14:14,230
Officer Neveu.

148
00:14:14,313 --> 00:14:15,940
Please, pardon the interruption.

149
00:14:16,024 --> 00:14:17,025
This is not the time.

150
00:14:17,191 --> 00:14:19,444
I received the crime-scene jpegs
at headquarters...

151
00:14:19,610 --> 00:14:21,446
...and I've deciphered the code.

152
00:14:21,779 --> 00:14:23,364
It's a Fibonacci sequence.

153
00:14:23,531 --> 00:14:24,991
That's the code Saunière left on the floor.

154
00:14:25,074 --> 00:14:26,075
Fibonacci?

155
00:14:26,284 --> 00:14:28,411
Headquarters sent me to explain, captain.

156
00:14:28,494 --> 00:14:29,954
It is the Fibonacci sequence.

157
00:14:30,038 --> 00:14:31,372
The numbers are out of order.

158
00:14:31,456 --> 00:14:34,459
But before that, I have an urgent
message for Professor Langdon.

159
00:14:34,542 --> 00:14:35,585
Right?

160
00:14:36,169 --> 00:14:37,420
Pardon me?

161
00:14:39,797 --> 00:14:42,925
I'm Sophie Neveu, French
police, Cryptology.

162
00:14:43,051 --> 00:14:45,053
Your embassy called Division.

163
00:14:49,891 --> 00:14:54,145
I'm sorry, monsieur, they said
it was a matter of life and death.

164
00:14:55,063 --> 00:14:58,024
This is the number
of your embassy's messaging service.

165
00:14:59,067 --> 00:15:00,443
Well, thank you.

166
00:15:07,825 --> 00:15:09,994
Hello, you've reached
the home of Sophie Neveu.

167
00:15:10,828 --> 00:15:14,082
Miss Neveu? This...

168
00:15:14,165 --> 00:15:15,416
No. That's the right number.

169
00:15:15,500 --> 00:15:17,919
You have to dial an access code
to pick up your messages.

170
00:15:18,002 --> 00:15:19,087
But I'm getting...

171
00:15:19,170 --> 00:15:22,048
It's a three-digit code.
It's on the paper I gave you.

172
00:15:31,265 --> 00:15:34,435
Professor Langdon,
do not react to this message.

173
00:15:34,519 --> 00:15:37,105
You must follow my directions very closely

174
00:15:37,188 --> 00:15:40,399
and, above all,
reveal nothing to Captain Fache.

175
00:15:40,483 --> 00:15:42,527
You are in grave danger.

176
00:15:55,957 --> 00:15:57,500
Church of Saint-Sulpice.

177
00:15:57,708 --> 00:15:59,377
Good evening, Sister.

178
00:16:00,378 --> 00:16:04,173
I need you to show someone
our church tonight.

179
00:16:04,549 --> 00:16:06,008
Of course, Father.

180
00:16:06,551 --> 00:16:08,219
But so late?

181
00:16:09,470 --> 00:16:10,471
Wouldn't tomorrow...?

182
00:16:10,638 --> 00:16:15,393
This is a request from an
important bishop of Opus Dei.

183
00:16:16,102 --> 00:16:18,563
It would be my pleasure.

184
00:16:42,420 --> 00:16:45,590
There's been an accident. A friend.

185
00:16:45,673 --> 00:16:49,135
- I have to fly home in the morning.
- I see.

186
00:16:49,343 --> 00:16:51,179
Is there a restroom I could use?

187
00:16:51,262 --> 00:16:53,514
I just wanna splash some water on my face.

188
00:16:53,598 --> 00:16:54,765
Yes.

189
00:16:56,893 --> 00:16:59,687
She said it is meaningless.

190
00:17:00,479 --> 00:17:02,273
A mathematical joke.

191
00:17:03,274 --> 00:17:05,109
Is it meaningless?

192
00:17:07,778 --> 00:17:09,864
I'll take another look when I come back.

193
00:17:13,743 --> 00:17:16,162
I'm sorry. Of course.

194
00:17:30,134 --> 00:17:32,345
Do you have a message from Saunière?

195
00:17:33,054 --> 00:17:34,680
What are you talking about?

196
00:17:35,806 --> 00:17:37,266
Crazy old man.

197
00:17:37,475 --> 00:17:40,061
You have me confused with someone else.

198
00:17:40,269 --> 00:17:42,271
- I came here to...
- Check your jacket pocket.

199
00:17:43,564 --> 00:17:44,857
Just look.

200
00:17:48,945 --> 00:17:50,655
GPS tracking dot.

201
00:17:50,821 --> 00:17:53,991
Accurate within two feet
anywhere on the globe.

202
00:17:54,075 --> 00:17:57,119
The agent who picked you up
slipped it into your jacket

203
00:17:59,080 --> 00:18:01,165
in case you tried to run.

204
00:18:02,708 --> 00:18:05,336
We have you on a little leash, Professor.

205
00:18:05,670 --> 00:18:07,672
Why would I try to run?
I didn't do anything.

206
00:18:07,797 --> 00:18:11,926
So, what do you think about
the fourth line of text

207
00:18:12,009 --> 00:18:14,887
Fache wiped clean before you arrived?

208
00:18:20,977 --> 00:18:24,605
He brought you here to force
a confession, Professor Langdon.

209
00:18:28,276 --> 00:18:31,028
He's still in there? What's he doing?

210
00:18:31,112 --> 00:18:34,615
Fache isn't even looking
for other suspects, okay?

211
00:18:34,699 --> 00:18:36,200
He is sure you're guilty.

212
00:18:39,829 --> 00:18:42,415
When did Saunière contact you?

213
00:18:42,623 --> 00:18:43,958
- Today?
- Yes, yes.

214
00:18:44,041 --> 00:18:46,043
What time? What time?

215
00:18:46,127 --> 00:18:48,337
At 3:00. Around 3:00. 3:00.

216
00:18:48,421 --> 00:18:52,216
We call Fache "the Bull."
Once he starts, he doesn't stop.

217
00:18:52,341 --> 00:18:55,636
He can arrest you and detain you
for months while he builds a case.

218
00:18:55,720 --> 00:18:59,140
And by then whatever Saunière
wanted you to tell me will be useless.

219
00:18:59,223 --> 00:19:01,559
Lady, stop it! Just stop!

220
00:19:01,976 --> 00:19:03,477
Who are you?

221
00:19:08,399 --> 00:19:10,234
Look at the letters.

222
00:19:11,485 --> 00:19:12,945
"P.S."

223
00:19:13,362 --> 00:19:15,031
P.S., postscript.

224
00:19:16,407 --> 00:19:19,243
"Princess Sophie." Silly, I know.

225
00:19:19,327 --> 00:19:22,079
But I was only a girl
when I lived with him.

226
00:19:25,499 --> 00:19:28,044
Jacques Saunière was my grandfather.

227
00:19:33,215 --> 00:19:36,552
Apparently, it was his dying wish
that we meet.

228
00:19:38,346 --> 00:19:40,681
If you help me understand why

229
00:19:40,765 --> 00:19:44,435
I will get you to your embassy,
where we cannot arrest you.

230
00:19:45,686 --> 00:19:48,439
Fache was never gonna let me
just stroll out of here, was he?

231
00:19:49,148 --> 00:19:50,441
No.

232
00:19:51,359 --> 00:19:55,154
If we are to get away from here,
we must find another way.

233
00:20:03,954 --> 00:20:06,248
What exactly do you propose?

234
00:20:15,800 --> 00:20:18,636
Saunière was reading his book.

235
00:20:19,053 --> 00:20:21,013
"Blood trail."

236
00:20:23,015 --> 00:20:24,850
Excuse me, captain.

237
00:20:25,142 --> 00:20:27,103
We have a problem.

238
00:20:27,311 --> 00:20:30,314
Headquarters didn't send Sophie Neveu.

239
00:20:32,525 --> 00:20:33,734
What?

240
00:20:33,901 --> 00:20:37,321
Captain, look at this.

241
00:20:38,906 --> 00:20:40,157
He jumped!

242
00:20:40,741 --> 00:20:41,826
Shit.

243
00:20:43,994 --> 00:20:47,164
He's moving again. And fast.

244
00:20:48,749 --> 00:20:49,917
He must be in a car.

245
00:20:51,085 --> 00:20:55,297
He's going south on Pont du Carrousel.

246
00:21:04,014 --> 00:21:05,307
Bastard.

247
00:21:28,873 --> 00:21:31,584
That cop will check the whole lower floor.

248
00:21:35,546 --> 00:21:37,840
I will only take a moment.

249
00:21:38,340 --> 00:21:39,592
Of course.

250
00:21:48,309 --> 00:21:50,478
He is much older than I remember.

251
00:22:02,239 --> 00:22:05,618
I hadn't seen or spoken to him
in a very long time.

252
00:22:14,752 --> 00:22:18,714
He phoned my office today. Several times.

253
00:22:19,924 --> 00:22:22,927
He said it was a matter of life and death.

254
00:22:23,427 --> 00:22:26,764
I thought it was another trick
to get back in touch.

255
00:22:29,433 --> 00:22:32,228
It seems when he couldn't speak to me,

256
00:22:33,479 --> 00:22:35,481
he reached out to you.

257
00:22:52,540 --> 00:22:54,917
- Wait a minute.
- Professor?

258
00:22:56,627 --> 00:22:59,880
This is wrong. Yeah. See? This is wrong.

259
00:23:01,549 --> 00:23:05,135
The Fibonacci numbers only make sense
when they're in order.

260
00:23:05,219 --> 00:23:06,762
These are scrambled.

261
00:23:06,845 --> 00:23:10,599
If he was trying to reach out,
maybe he was doing it in code.

262
00:23:10,683 --> 00:23:12,560
Would you hold this, please?

263
00:23:15,104 --> 00:23:16,981
This phrase is meaningless.

264
00:23:19,024 --> 00:23:23,612
Unless you assume these letters
are out of order too.

265
00:23:23,696 --> 00:23:24,863
An anagram.

266
00:23:36,625 --> 00:23:38,419
You have eidetic memory?

267
00:23:38,711 --> 00:23:42,256
Not quite.
But I can pretty much remember what I see.

268
00:24:03,652 --> 00:24:05,571
Anagram is right.

269
00:24:06,989 --> 00:24:09,533
"O, Draconian devil. Oh,
lame saint" becomes

270
00:24:09,617 --> 00:24:12,244
"Leonardo da Vinci. The Mona Lisa."

271
00:24:12,578 --> 00:24:16,248
Professor, the Mona Lisa
is right over here.

272
00:24:22,755 --> 00:24:27,718
Look at this. He must have
thrown it from the window.

273
00:24:28,052 --> 00:24:29,678
Smart to hit the truck.

274
00:24:30,054 --> 00:24:33,599
What, you admire him now?

275
00:24:35,225 --> 00:24:37,311
We're stupid. Who did
we leave at the museum?

276
00:24:37,478 --> 00:24:40,230
Ledoux? Get him on the radio!

277
00:24:40,481 --> 00:24:43,525
Her smile is in the lower
spatial frequencies.

278
00:24:43,609 --> 00:24:47,404
The horizon is significantly lower
on the left than it is on the right.

279
00:24:47,488 --> 00:24:48,614
Why?

280
00:24:48,697 --> 00:24:52,201
Well, see, she appears larger
from the left than on the right.

281
00:24:52,284 --> 00:24:55,454
Historically, the left was female,
the right was male.

282
00:24:55,537 --> 00:24:57,247
There. Blood.

283
00:25:05,714 --> 00:25:06,840
Hey.

284
00:25:08,509 --> 00:25:11,136
"So dark the con of man."

285
00:25:11,929 --> 00:25:15,265
No. It doesn't say that.

286
00:25:15,432 --> 00:25:17,768
Is it another anagram? Can you break it?

287
00:25:22,690 --> 00:25:25,150
Professor, hurry. Hurry!

288
00:25:26,819 --> 00:25:29,780
Moon. Sermon. Charms.

289
00:25:29,988 --> 00:25:33,951
Demons. Omens. Codes. Monks. Ranks. Rocks.

290
00:25:34,034 --> 00:25:35,285
Madonna of the Rocks.

291
00:25:36,036 --> 00:25:37,121
Da Vinci.

292
00:25:47,506 --> 00:25:49,258
Careful. Careful.

293
00:25:56,682 --> 00:26:00,561
This can't be this. The fleur-de-lis.

294
00:26:40,392 --> 00:26:42,060
It was Saunière's.

295
00:26:42,686 --> 00:26:45,647
I remember finding it
once when I was a girl.

296
00:26:46,523 --> 00:26:48,734
He'd promised he'd give it to me one day.

297
00:26:49,526 --> 00:26:51,862
Have you ever heard
those words before, Sophie?

298
00:26:51,945 --> 00:26:53,447
"So dark the con of man"?

299
00:26:53,530 --> 00:26:55,157
No. Have you?

300
00:26:55,240 --> 00:26:58,869
When you were a child,
were you aware of any secret gatherings?

301
00:26:59,995 --> 00:27:02,372
Anything ritualistic in nature?

302
00:27:02,539 --> 00:27:05,793
Meetings your grandfather
would've wanted kept secret?

303
00:27:06,001 --> 00:27:09,505
Was there ever any talk of something
called the Priory of Sion?

304
00:27:09,630 --> 00:27:12,549
The what? Why are you asking these things?

305
00:27:12,758 --> 00:27:15,803
The Priory of Sion is a myth.

306
00:27:15,886 --> 00:27:18,138
One of the world's oldest
and most secret societies,

307
00:27:18,222 --> 00:27:22,726
with leaders like Sir Isaac Newton,
da Vinci himself.

308
00:27:23,060 --> 00:27:24,895
The fleur-de-lis is their crest.

309
00:27:24,978 --> 00:27:27,689
They're guardians of a secret
they supposedly refer to

310
00:27:27,773 --> 00:27:30,025
as "the dark con of man."

311
00:27:30,567 --> 00:27:31,985
But what secret?

312
00:27:32,528 --> 00:27:37,825
The Priory of Sion protects
the source of God's power on Earth.

313
00:27:46,750 --> 00:27:48,627
I can't do this by myself.

314
00:27:49,169 --> 00:27:52,214
I'm in enough trouble as it is.
That's my embassy.

315
00:27:52,297 --> 00:27:53,382
Please.

316
00:27:53,465 --> 00:27:55,926
- Even if we could get out of this...
- Okay.

317
00:28:33,046 --> 00:28:36,425
No, no, no. You're not gonna make it.
You're not gonna make it!

318
00:28:44,057 --> 00:28:45,392
Well, that was...

319
00:28:54,276 --> 00:28:56,028
We need to get out of sight.

320
00:29:10,667 --> 00:29:12,961
Christ, give me strength.

321
00:29:25,515 --> 00:29:29,519
You are a ghost.

322
00:29:30,854 --> 00:29:33,148
Christ, give me strength.

323
00:30:10,435 --> 00:30:13,063
Stealing in a house of God!

324
00:30:26,410 --> 00:30:28,412
You are an angel.

325
00:30:30,664 --> 00:30:32,916
Christ, give me strength.

326
00:30:58,400 --> 00:31:00,569
You have powerful friends.

327
00:31:01,278 --> 00:31:04,448
Bishop Aringarosa has been kind to me.

328
00:31:05,032 --> 00:31:09,036
I could not miss this chance
to pray inside the Saint-Sulpice.

329
00:31:09,911 --> 00:31:12,372
A pity you couldn't wait for morning.

330
00:31:12,456 --> 00:31:14,458
The light is not ideal.

331
00:31:15,417 --> 00:31:19,546
Tell me, Sister, please, of the Rose Line.

332
00:31:19,963 --> 00:31:25,135
A rose line is any line that goes from
the North to South Poles.

333
00:31:25,260 --> 00:31:30,140
Set into the streets of Paris,
135 brass markers

334
00:31:30,223 --> 00:31:33,101
mark the world's first prime meridian

335
00:31:33,185 --> 00:31:35,604
which passed through this very church.

336
00:31:35,687 --> 00:31:37,522
It hides beneath the Rose.

337
00:31:37,689 --> 00:31:38,899
I'm sorry?

338
00:31:40,317 --> 00:31:41,568
Sister.

339
00:31:44,279 --> 00:31:47,574
I do not want to keep you.
I will show myself out.

340
00:31:50,786 --> 00:31:51,912
I insist.

341
00:31:56,166 --> 00:31:59,086
May the peace of the Lord be with you.

342
00:32:00,712 --> 00:32:02,130
And with you.

343
00:32:15,352 --> 00:32:20,857
They found Neveu's car
abandoned at the train station.

344
00:32:21,608 --> 00:32:26,530
And two tickets to Brussels paid for
with Langdon's credit card.

345
00:32:26,738 --> 00:32:28,198
A decoy, I'm sure.

346
00:32:28,406 --> 00:32:30,867
All the same, send an
officer to the station.

347
00:32:31,076 --> 00:32:33,703
Question all the taxi drivers.
I'll put this on the wire.

348
00:32:33,954 --> 00:32:36,748
Interpol? We're not sure he's guilty.

349
00:32:37,082 --> 00:32:40,877
I know he's guilty. Beyond a doubt.

350
00:32:41,044 --> 00:32:44,005
Robert Langdon is guilty.

351
00:32:52,973 --> 00:32:54,224
This is the Bois de Boulogne?

352
00:32:54,307 --> 00:32:57,144
We should be safe in this park
for a few minutes.

353
00:33:49,112 --> 00:33:50,405
Stay here.

354
00:33:52,115 --> 00:33:53,450
Police.

355
00:33:54,951 --> 00:33:56,286
What do you want?

356
00:34:01,833 --> 00:34:03,919
Fifty euros for all your stuff.

357
00:34:06,129 --> 00:34:08,298
Go and get something to eat.

358
00:34:28,276 --> 00:34:30,153
Did it ever occur to you
that could be dangerous?

359
00:34:30,237 --> 00:34:33,448
No. And now we have a place to think.

360
00:34:34,199 --> 00:34:35,909
Any ideas, Professor?

361
00:34:37,118 --> 00:34:40,664
You could've just handed me
a piece of a UFO from Area 51.

362
00:34:42,791 --> 00:34:44,834
"What's the next step?"

363
00:34:45,377 --> 00:34:47,003
With him, it's always,

364
00:34:47,087 --> 00:34:50,173
"Sophie, what's the next step?"

365
00:34:50,840 --> 00:34:52,425
Puzzles.

366
00:34:52,509 --> 00:34:53,843
Codes.

367
00:34:54,761 --> 00:34:55,929
A treasure hunt.

368
00:35:00,517 --> 00:35:01,768
To find his killer.

369
00:35:06,022 --> 00:35:09,442
Maybe there is something
about this Priory of Sion.

370
00:35:09,651 --> 00:35:10,652
I hope not.

371
00:35:10,902 --> 00:35:15,699
Any Priory story ends in bloodshed.
They were butchered by the Church.

372
00:35:16,074 --> 00:35:19,244
It all started over a thousand years ago
when a French king

373
00:35:19,327 --> 00:35:21,746
conquered the holy city of Jerusalem.

374
00:35:22,080 --> 00:35:25,500
This crusade, one of the most
massive and sweeping in history,

375
00:35:25,583 --> 00:35:29,212
was actually orchestrated
by a secret brotherhood,

376
00:35:29,296 --> 00:35:30,463
the Priory of Sion

377
00:35:30,547 --> 00:35:34,843
and their military arm,
the Knights Templar.

378
00:35:35,385 --> 00:35:38,430
But the Templars were created
to protect the Holy Land.

379
00:35:38,638 --> 00:35:42,642
That was a cover to hide their true goal,
according to this myth.

380
00:35:43,101 --> 00:35:46,187
Supposedly the invasion
was to find an artifact

381
00:35:46,271 --> 00:35:48,189
lost since the time of Christ.

382
00:35:48,273 --> 00:35:52,402
An artifact, it was said,
the Church would kill to possess.

383
00:35:52,902 --> 00:35:55,488
Did they find it, this buried treasure?

384
00:35:56,698 --> 00:35:57,949
Put it this way.

385
00:35:58,074 --> 00:36:00,493
One day the Templars
simply stopped searching.

386
00:36:01,244 --> 00:36:04,414
They quit the Holy Land
and traveled directly to Rome.

387
00:36:04,914 --> 00:36:06,916
Whether they blackmailed the papacy

388
00:36:07,000 --> 00:36:09,336
or the Church bought their silence,
no one knows.

389
00:36:09,419 --> 00:36:13,590
But it is a fact the papacy
declared these Priory knights,

390
00:36:13,673 --> 00:36:17,302
these Knights Templar, of limitless power.

391
00:36:18,511 --> 00:36:21,765
By the 1300s,
the Templars had grown too powerful.

392
00:36:21,848 --> 00:36:23,266
Too threatening.

393
00:36:23,516 --> 00:36:25,685
So the Vatican issued secret orders

394
00:36:26,102 --> 00:36:28,897
to be opened simultaneously
all across Europe.

395
00:36:29,773 --> 00:36:33,526
The Pope had declared
the Knights Templar Satan worshipers

396
00:36:33,610 --> 00:36:37,822
and said God had charged him
with cleansing the Earth of these heretics.

397
00:36:38,323 --> 00:36:40,658
The plan went off like clockwork.

398
00:36:41,368 --> 00:36:43,995
The Templars were all but exterminated.

399
00:36:44,079 --> 00:36:48,291
The date was October 13, 1307. A Friday.

400
00:36:48,541 --> 00:36:50,251
Friday the 13th.

401
00:36:51,127 --> 00:36:54,130
The Pope sent troops
to claim the Priory's treasure,

402
00:36:54,214 --> 00:36:55,799
but they found nothing.

403
00:36:55,965 --> 00:36:59,427
The few surviving Knights of the Priory
had vanished,

404
00:36:59,511 --> 00:37:02,555
and the search for
their sacred artifact began again.

405
00:37:02,639 --> 00:37:06,017
What artifact?
I've never heard about any of this.

406
00:37:06,976 --> 00:37:08,478
Yes, you have.

407
00:37:08,853 --> 00:37:10,605
Almost everyone on Earth has.

408
00:37:11,606 --> 00:37:14,234
You just know it as the Holy Grail.

409
00:37:20,365 --> 00:37:23,827
Please, Saunière thought he knew
the location of the Holy Grail?

410
00:37:24,911 --> 00:37:26,830
Maybe more than that.

411
00:37:26,996 --> 00:37:30,875
This cross and the flower,
this could be very old. But look.

412
00:37:30,959 --> 00:37:35,505
This metal here underneath is much newer,
and there's a modern ID stamp.

413
00:37:36,339 --> 00:37:37,757
"Haxo 24."

414
00:37:40,385 --> 00:37:43,763
And these dots.
These dots are read by a laser.

415
00:37:43,972 --> 00:37:47,684
This is more than a pendant.
This is a key your grandfather left you.

416
00:37:47,851 --> 00:37:50,019
He left us, Professor.

417
00:37:51,813 --> 00:37:56,151
And vingt-quatre Haxo,
it's not an ID stamp.

418
00:37:56,651 --> 00:37:58,528
It's a street address.

419
00:38:03,450 --> 00:38:05,034
This is Jacques Saunière.

420
00:38:05,410 --> 00:38:08,246
Please leave a message after the tone.

421
00:38:08,955 --> 00:38:11,332
Please, Monsieur Saunière,
pick up the phone.

422
00:38:11,583 --> 00:38:13,084
This is Sandrine Bieil.

423
00:38:13,334 --> 00:38:15,587
I have called the list.

424
00:38:16,004 --> 00:38:17,922
I fear the other guardians are dead.

425
00:38:18,506 --> 00:38:20,425
The lie has been told.

426
00:38:20,758 --> 00:38:22,677
The floor panel has been broken.

427
00:38:23,344 --> 00:38:26,764
Please, monsieur, pick up the phone.
I beg you.

428
00:38:26,848 --> 00:38:28,558
Job 38, verse 11.

429
00:38:30,351 --> 00:38:32,270
Do you know it, Sister?

430
00:38:34,063 --> 00:38:35,815
Job 38:11.

431
00:38:37,484 --> 00:38:41,738
"Hitherto shalt thou come but no further."

432
00:38:42,489 --> 00:38:43,907
"But no further."

433
00:38:48,036 --> 00:38:49,913
Do you mock me?

434
00:38:52,790 --> 00:38:54,918
Where is the keystone?

435
00:38:55,919 --> 00:38:57,670
I do not know.

436
00:38:58,713 --> 00:38:59,839
No.

437
00:39:02,133 --> 00:39:04,511
You are a sister of the Church

438
00:39:06,846 --> 00:39:10,350
and yet you serve them, the Priory.

439
00:39:10,433 --> 00:39:14,354
Jesus had but one true message, that...

440
00:39:27,367 --> 00:39:30,078
Come, you saints of God.

441
00:39:30,995 --> 00:39:33,623
Hasten, angels of the Lord.

442
00:39:34,374 --> 00:39:37,126
To receive her soul.

443
00:39:37,585 --> 00:39:42,131
And bring her to the sight of the Almighty.

444
00:40:00,650 --> 00:40:02,318
Welcome, Bishop.

445
00:40:03,194 --> 00:40:05,238
This council is convened.

446
00:40:13,830 --> 00:40:17,250
Our words shall never pass these walls.

447
00:40:20,336 --> 00:40:22,005
What business, say you?

448
00:40:23,965 --> 00:40:26,092
As you know, my request for funds...

449
00:40:26,175 --> 00:40:30,013
Yes, 20 million euro
in untraceable bearer bonds.

450
00:40:30,680 --> 00:40:33,975
A tad more than petty cash.
Wouldn't you say, Bishop?

451
00:40:35,768 --> 00:40:40,398
I only offer a route to the renewal
of faith for all men.

452
00:40:40,523 --> 00:40:41,941
How humble.

453
00:40:42,025 --> 00:40:44,819
Our savior, Bishop Aringarosa.

454
00:40:44,902 --> 00:40:46,446
How dare you presume to...

455
00:40:46,529 --> 00:40:48,239
I do not presume, I act!

456
00:40:48,740 --> 00:40:52,619
The Vatican's unwillingness to support us
is both impious and cowardly.

457
00:40:52,910 --> 00:40:57,040
Blood is being spilled because true
Christian values lie in ruins. No more!

458
00:40:57,707 --> 00:41:00,918
This council has forgotten
its very purpose.

459
00:41:03,630 --> 00:41:08,468
Tonight, the Grail will be destroyed.

460
00:41:08,551 --> 00:41:12,096
The Priory's few remaining members
will be silenced.

461
00:41:20,313 --> 00:41:24,567
I was contacted by a man
who calls himself only "the Teacher."

462
00:41:27,111 --> 00:41:29,697
Two prostitutes identified
Langdon and Neveu...

463
00:41:29,864 --> 00:41:32,075
...getting into a taxi
in the Bois de Boulogne.

464
00:41:42,001 --> 00:41:43,920
Because of your expertise?

465
00:41:45,088 --> 00:41:46,673
- I'm sorry?
- About the Priory.

466
00:41:46,756 --> 00:41:49,217
Do you think that's why
Saunière sought you out?

467
00:41:49,801 --> 00:41:53,012
I can think of dozens of scholars
who know a lot more about it.

468
00:41:53,096 --> 00:41:57,183
Actually, I didn't think
he liked me very much.

469
00:41:57,850 --> 00:42:01,396
Once made a joke at my expense.
Got a big laugh out of it.

470
00:42:01,479 --> 00:42:02,814
What was it?

471
00:42:15,993 --> 00:42:17,787
How may I help you?

472
00:42:23,668 --> 00:42:25,962
The door to the right, please.

473
00:42:44,439 --> 00:42:47,108
Good evening. I am André Vernet,
the night manager.

474
00:42:48,609 --> 00:42:51,863
I take it this is your first visit
to our establishment?

475
00:42:52,655 --> 00:42:53,781
Yes.

476
00:42:54,490 --> 00:42:55,825
Understood.

477
00:42:56,659 --> 00:42:58,077
Keys are often passed on

478
00:42:58,161 --> 00:43:01,873
and first-time users
are sometimes uncertain of protocol.

479
00:43:03,666 --> 00:43:06,502
Keys are essentially
numbered Swiss accounts.

480
00:43:08,087 --> 00:43:10,631
Often willed through generations.

481
00:43:13,551 --> 00:43:16,012
Is it yours, mademoiselle?

482
00:43:18,139 --> 00:43:21,142
The shortest safety-deposit-box lease
is 50 years.

483
00:43:22,143 --> 00:43:24,187
And what's your longest account?

484
00:43:24,395 --> 00:43:25,980
Quite a bit longer.

485
00:43:26,439 --> 00:43:29,066
Technologies change, keys are updated.

486
00:43:34,489 --> 00:43:36,240
Once the computer confirms your key,

487
00:43:36,324 --> 00:43:39,368
enter your account number
and your box is retrieved.

488
00:43:40,077 --> 00:43:42,538
The room is yours, as long as you like.

489
00:43:47,543 --> 00:43:50,755
What if I lost track of my account number?

490
00:43:51,339 --> 00:43:52,799
How might I recover it?

491
00:43:55,051 --> 00:43:57,762
I'm afraid each key is paired
with a 10-digit number

492
00:43:57,845 --> 00:43:59,972
known only to the account bearer.

493
00:44:00,056 --> 00:44:02,141
I hope you manage to remember it.

494
00:44:02,767 --> 00:44:05,394
A single wrong entry disables the system.

495
00:44:12,360 --> 00:44:13,569
- Ten.
- Ten.

496
00:44:13,653 --> 00:44:16,197
Your grandfather's Fibonacci sequence.

497
00:44:19,283 --> 00:44:21,661
Scrambled, unscrambled?

498
00:44:22,578 --> 00:44:23,913
Unscrambled.

499
00:44:24,580 --> 00:44:26,249
It's your key.

500
00:44:30,962 --> 00:44:34,674
Funny, I don't even like history.

501
00:44:37,802 --> 00:44:42,306
I've never seen much good
come from looking to the past.

502
00:44:49,772 --> 00:44:51,274
Moment of truth.

503
00:45:35,943 --> 00:45:38,487
My God. I don't believe this.

504
00:45:38,905 --> 00:45:40,072
A rose.

505
00:45:44,911 --> 00:45:46,746
The rose was a symbol for the Holy Grail.

506
00:45:49,624 --> 00:45:51,584
Forgive the intrusion.

507
00:45:51,667 --> 00:45:54,795
I'm afraid the police arrived
more quickly than anticipated.

508
00:45:55,922 --> 00:45:57,673
You must follow me, please.

509
00:45:57,882 --> 00:45:59,258
For your own safety.

510
00:45:59,634 --> 00:46:01,344
You knew they were coming?

511
00:46:01,427 --> 00:46:04,263
My guard alerted me to your status
when you arrived.

512
00:46:04,347 --> 00:46:07,350
Yours is one of our oldest
and highest-level accounts.

513
00:46:07,433 --> 00:46:09,685
It includes a safe-passage clause.

514
00:46:09,852 --> 00:46:11,020
Safe passage?

515
00:46:11,938 --> 00:46:15,191
If you would step inside, please.
Time is of the essence.

516
00:46:18,319 --> 00:46:19,570
In there?

517
00:46:34,752 --> 00:46:36,545
Hey, is there a problem?

518
00:46:36,796 --> 00:46:39,423
Good evening, sir. Police.

519
00:46:39,882 --> 00:46:43,970
I just drive from here to Zurich.
Not French, English?

520
00:46:44,220 --> 00:46:45,346
- English?
- Yes.

521
00:46:46,722 --> 00:46:49,392
We are looking for two criminals.

522
00:46:50,685 --> 00:46:53,562
You came to the right place.
They're all criminals here.

523
00:46:55,356 --> 00:46:57,692
Would you mind opening the hold?

524
00:46:58,234 --> 00:47:01,862
Please. You think they trust us,
the wages I get paid?

525
00:47:01,946 --> 00:47:03,948
You don't have keys to your own truck?

526
00:47:04,031 --> 00:47:06,742
It's armored.
Keys get sent to the destination.

527
00:47:06,909 --> 00:47:08,995
You mind? I'm on a schedule here.

528
00:47:12,540 --> 00:47:16,919
And do all the drivers wear a Rolex?

529
00:47:17,420 --> 00:47:18,504
What?

530
00:47:20,923 --> 00:47:22,591
This piece of shit.

531
00:47:22,675 --> 00:47:24,552
Forty euros in Barbés.

532
00:47:24,635 --> 00:47:25,761
Yours for 35.

533
00:47:26,429 --> 00:47:27,513
No, no, no.

534
00:47:27,596 --> 00:47:29,432
- Thirty.
- No. It's okay, it's okay.

535
00:47:29,557 --> 00:47:32,309
- Come on, 30?
- I said, no!

536
00:47:32,893 --> 00:47:34,020
Move along!

537
00:47:47,450 --> 00:47:48,659
Now we wait.

538
00:47:48,743 --> 00:47:51,454
The Teacher will call and tell me
where to deliver the money.

539
00:47:51,537 --> 00:47:54,874
You have put tremendous faith
in this Teacher of yours.

540
00:47:54,957 --> 00:47:59,378
Yes, I have. And I have given
him an angel to do his will.

541
00:47:59,879 --> 00:48:03,257
For surely there is no better soldier
for God than my Silas.

542
00:48:04,341 --> 00:48:08,054
I firmly resolve, with the help of
thy grace, to confess my sins...

543
00:48:08,262 --> 00:48:13,059
...to do penance and to amend my life.

544
00:48:13,350 --> 00:48:14,351
Amen.

545
00:48:29,700 --> 00:48:31,327
The Holy Grail.

546
00:48:32,119 --> 00:48:37,083
A magic cup.
The source of God's power on earth.

547
00:48:37,166 --> 00:48:38,459
It's nonsense.

548
00:48:39,418 --> 00:48:41,337
You don't believe in God.

549
00:48:42,213 --> 00:48:43,339
No.

550
00:48:44,298 --> 00:48:45,800
Just people.

551
00:48:47,093 --> 00:48:49,678
Sometimes that they can be kind.

552
00:48:51,055 --> 00:48:53,641
Are you a God-fearing man, Professor?

553
00:48:55,184 --> 00:48:57,019
I was raised a Catholic.

554
00:48:57,686 --> 00:48:59,522
Well, that's not really an answer.

555
00:49:02,149 --> 00:49:03,859
Professor, are you okay?

556
00:49:04,902 --> 00:49:06,529
Go ahead, open it.

557
00:49:07,363 --> 00:49:08,405
Go on.

558
00:49:15,538 --> 00:49:16,872
A cryptex.

559
00:49:18,165 --> 00:49:20,668
They are used to keep secrets.

560
00:49:21,460 --> 00:49:23,587
It's da Vinci's design.

561
00:49:24,338 --> 00:49:27,758
You write the information
on a papyrus scroll

562
00:49:27,842 --> 00:49:32,930
which is then rolled around
a thin glass vial of vinegar.

563
00:49:33,013 --> 00:49:36,308
If you force it open, the vial breaks,

564
00:49:36,392 --> 00:49:39,061
vinegar dissolves papyrus,

565
00:49:40,980 --> 00:49:43,566
and your secret is lost forever.

566
00:49:43,941 --> 00:49:46,110
The only way to access the information

567
00:49:46,193 --> 00:49:51,824
is to spell out the password with these
five dials, each with 26 letters.

568
00:49:52,867 --> 00:49:56,745
That's 12 million possibilities.

569
00:49:57,496 --> 00:50:01,000
I've never met a girl
who knew that much about a cryptex.

570
00:50:02,334 --> 00:50:04,587
Saunière made one for me once.

571
00:50:12,553 --> 00:50:15,764
My grandfather gave me a wagon.

572
00:50:18,309 --> 00:50:20,603
This clearly is not the Holy Grail.

573
00:50:24,481 --> 00:50:25,649
Come on.

574
00:50:25,941 --> 00:50:27,401
Please, you're not all right.

575
00:50:30,779 --> 00:50:32,239
May I try something?

576
00:50:32,907 --> 00:50:34,491
I don't know why it works.

577
00:50:35,409 --> 00:50:38,454
My mother used to do it
when I was scared, I think.

578
00:50:39,330 --> 00:50:40,623
You think?

579
00:50:41,415 --> 00:50:42,499
Yes.

580
00:50:54,386 --> 00:50:56,263
Feeling better, Sophie?

581
00:51:08,192 --> 00:51:12,655
My parents died in a car crash
with my brother.

582
00:51:13,822 --> 00:51:15,157
I was four.

583
00:51:17,159 --> 00:51:18,535
I'm sorry.

584
00:51:19,912 --> 00:51:21,830
It was many years ago.

585
00:51:37,513 --> 00:51:38,764
Better?

586
00:51:41,517 --> 00:51:42,518
Yeah.

587
00:51:43,310 --> 00:51:44,436
Okay.

588
00:52:10,546 --> 00:52:13,132
Twenty years waiting
for someone to come for that box,

589
00:52:13,215 --> 00:52:15,759
and now it's you two murderers.
Bring it to me.

590
00:52:16,719 --> 00:52:18,387
I don't know what you're talking about.

591
00:52:19,596 --> 00:52:21,390
All right! Okay!

592
00:52:22,224 --> 00:52:23,225
Right now!

593
00:52:33,694 --> 00:52:34,695
Step back!

594
00:52:38,657 --> 00:52:41,076
No one will lose sleep
over a couple on a killing spree.

595
00:52:44,246 --> 00:52:45,289
Turn around.

596
00:52:46,582 --> 00:52:48,000
Turn around!

597
00:52:48,584 --> 00:52:50,252
You too, mademoiselle.

598
00:53:13,025 --> 00:53:14,193
Sophie!

599
00:53:14,985 --> 00:53:16,362
Get in the truck!

600
00:53:16,862 --> 00:53:18,447
I'll drive! Hurry!

601
00:53:47,601 --> 00:53:51,814
What happened between you
and your grandfather, exactly?

602
00:53:53,440 --> 00:53:57,194
I've jammed my shoulder,
I've been shot at, I'm bleeding.

603
00:53:57,319 --> 00:53:58,904
I need to know.

604
00:53:59,154 --> 00:54:02,908
You say he raised you,
but you two don't talk anymore.

605
00:54:02,991 --> 00:54:04,785
You call him by his last name.

606
00:54:05,369 --> 00:54:07,579
You say you hate history.

607
00:54:07,663 --> 00:54:10,082
Nobody hates history.
They hate their own histories.

608
00:54:10,165 --> 00:54:12,167
So now you're a psychologist too?

609
00:54:12,626 --> 00:54:17,214
What if Saunière had started
to groom you for the Priory?

610
00:54:17,297 --> 00:54:18,757
What do you mean, groom me?

611
00:54:18,841 --> 00:54:22,094
Your grandfather gave you puzzles
and cryptex as a child.

612
00:54:22,177 --> 00:54:26,181
So you are saying all this is real?
The Priory, the Holy Grail?

613
00:54:26,390 --> 00:54:29,643
We've been dragged into a world
of people who think this stuff is real.

614
00:54:29,726 --> 00:54:31,854
- Real enough to kill for.
- Who?

615
00:54:38,068 --> 00:54:40,612
I'm out of my field here.

616
00:54:43,031 --> 00:54:48,328
I do know a Grail historian,
absolutely obsessed with Priory myth.

617
00:54:48,996 --> 00:54:51,290
An Englishman, lives here in France.

618
00:54:51,373 --> 00:54:53,000
Do you trust this man?

619
00:54:54,126 --> 00:54:55,669
I hope you can.

620
00:55:05,262 --> 00:55:08,098
It seems you're not a driver at all.

621
00:55:09,933 --> 00:55:14,730
Apparently, you lost your tongue
along with your truck.

622
00:55:15,397 --> 00:55:18,066
You think you're in pain now, André Vernet?

623
00:55:18,484 --> 00:55:22,488
My cause is worth your life. Understand?

624
00:55:26,825 --> 00:55:28,410
What do you want?

625
00:55:28,744 --> 00:55:33,999
Your truck carries a homing device.
Activate it.

626
00:55:41,632 --> 00:55:44,343
Please wait. I'll see if he's available.

627
00:55:44,468 --> 00:55:46,345
It's on the wrong side.

628
00:55:46,428 --> 00:55:49,056
Leigh likes all things to be English,
including his cars.

629
00:55:49,139 --> 00:55:52,267
Robert! Do I owe you money?

630
00:55:53,018 --> 00:55:56,021
Leigh, my friend,

631
00:55:56,104 --> 00:55:59,191
care to open up for an old colleague?

632
00:55:59,274 --> 00:56:00,984
- Of course.
- Thank you.

633
00:56:01,818 --> 00:56:04,238
But first, a test of honor.

634
00:56:04,613 --> 00:56:06,323
Three questions.

635
00:56:09,618 --> 00:56:10,953
Fire away.

636
00:56:11,036 --> 00:56:12,454
Your first.

637
00:56:12,663 --> 00:56:15,332
Shall I serve coffee or tea?

638
00:56:16,208 --> 00:56:17,709
Tea, of course.

639
00:56:17,793 --> 00:56:18,961
Excellent.

640
00:56:19,044 --> 00:56:21,338
Second. Milk or lemon?

641
00:56:22,381 --> 00:56:23,423
Milk?

642
00:56:24,800 --> 00:56:27,219
That would depend on the tea.

643
00:56:27,302 --> 00:56:28,387
Correct.

644
00:56:29,304 --> 00:56:33,475
And now the third
and most grave of inquiries.

645
00:56:33,600 --> 00:56:39,106
In which year did a Harvard sculler
out-row an Oxford man at Henley?

646
00:56:46,530 --> 00:56:50,284
Surely such a travesty has never occurred.

647
00:56:50,909 --> 00:56:52,786
Your heart is true.

648
00:56:53,662 --> 00:56:54,997
You may pass.

649
00:56:56,832 --> 00:56:59,167
Welcome to Château Villette.

650
00:57:02,087 --> 00:57:04,715
The truck's signal is coming online.

651
00:57:04,923 --> 00:57:06,341
It's about time.

652
00:57:10,095 --> 00:57:11,722
Locked on and tracking, sir.

653
00:57:14,558 --> 00:57:17,978
Very good. Tell Collet not to move in
until I get there.

654
00:57:19,563 --> 00:57:23,025
Attention! All of Collet's units
to Château Villette.

655
00:57:23,942 --> 00:57:27,279
The suspects Neveu and Langdon
are likely at that location.

656
00:57:43,587 --> 00:57:44,921
Aringarosa.

657
00:57:55,891 --> 00:57:58,894
I still don't know why he put you into this

658
00:57:59,603 --> 00:58:01,521
and I'm sorry.

659
00:58:06,610 --> 00:58:10,447
But I'm also very glad.

660
00:58:28,715 --> 00:58:31,385
You are requested to make yourself at home.

661
00:58:39,685 --> 00:58:40,852
Robert!

662
00:58:41,937 --> 00:58:44,523
And you travel with a maiden, it seems.

663
00:58:44,856 --> 00:58:48,068
Sir Leigh Teabing,
may I present Miss Sophie Neveu.

664
00:58:48,151 --> 00:58:50,278
Sophie, Sir Leigh Teabing.

665
00:58:50,654 --> 00:58:54,491
It's an honor to welcome you...

666
00:58:55,117 --> 00:58:57,202
...even though it's late.

667
00:58:57,285 --> 00:59:01,123
Thank you for having us.
I realize it's quite late.

668
00:59:02,416 --> 00:59:05,419
So late, mademoiselle, it's almost early.

669
00:59:08,046 --> 00:59:09,673
What a lovely smile you have.

670
00:59:12,008 --> 00:59:13,009
Earl Grey?

671
00:59:13,719 --> 00:59:14,803
Lemon.

672
00:59:15,512 --> 00:59:16,638
Correct.

673
00:59:37,534 --> 00:59:39,786
Château Villette. Yes.

674
00:59:41,496 --> 00:59:43,582
A dramatic late-night arrival.

675
00:59:43,915 --> 00:59:46,543
What can an old cripple do for you, Robert?

676
00:59:47,461 --> 00:59:51,339
We wanna talk about the Priory of Sion.

677
00:59:51,506 --> 00:59:52,716
The keepers?

678
00:59:53,633 --> 00:59:54,885
The secret war?

679
00:59:54,968 --> 00:59:56,970
Sorry for all the mystery.

680
00:59:57,888 --> 01:00:00,974
Leigh, I'm into something here
that I cannot understand.

681
01:00:01,391 --> 01:00:02,517
You?

682
01:00:03,226 --> 01:00:06,605
- Really?
- Not without your help.

683
01:00:07,022 --> 01:00:10,233
Playing to my vanity, Robert.
You should be ashamed.

684
01:00:10,317 --> 01:00:11,526
Not if it works.

685
01:00:14,112 --> 01:00:16,281
There are always four.

686
01:00:17,073 --> 01:00:20,202
The Grand Master and the three sénéchaux

687
01:00:20,410 --> 01:00:23,830
make up the primary guardians of the Grail.

688
01:00:25,749 --> 01:00:27,709
Thank you, Remy. That'll be all for now.

689
01:00:34,299 --> 01:00:37,761
The Priory's members
span our very globe itself.

690
01:00:37,844 --> 01:00:42,390
Philippe de Chérisey
exposed that as a hoax in 1967.

691
01:00:42,474 --> 01:00:44,601
And that is what they want you to believe.

692
01:00:45,352 --> 01:00:48,230
The Priory is charged with a single task.

693
01:00:48,355 --> 01:00:51,817
To protect the greatest secret
in modern history.

694
01:00:51,900 --> 01:00:54,444
The source of God's power on Earth.

695
01:00:54,528 --> 01:00:56,279
No, that's a common misunderstanding.

696
01:00:56,404 --> 01:01:01,034
The Priory protects the source
of the Church's power on Earth.

697
01:01:02,035 --> 01:01:03,328
The Holy Grail.

698
01:01:03,870 --> 01:01:05,622
I don't understand.

699
01:01:05,705 --> 01:01:09,835
What power? Some magic dishes?

700
01:01:10,585 --> 01:01:14,673
Robert. Has he been telling you
that the Holy Grail is a cup?

701
01:01:29,229 --> 01:01:33,066
The Good Book did not arrive
by facsimile from heaven.

702
01:01:33,775 --> 01:01:38,405
The Bible as we know it
was finally presided over by one man.

703
01:01:38,488 --> 01:01:40,240
The pagan emperor Constantine.

704
01:01:40,657 --> 01:01:42,784
I thought Constantine was a Christian.

705
01:01:42,993 --> 01:01:46,037
Hardly, no. He was a lifelong pagan

706
01:01:46,121 --> 01:01:48,748
who was baptized on his deathbed.

707
01:01:48,832 --> 01:01:51,626
Constantine was Rome's supreme holy man.

708
01:01:52,627 --> 01:01:54,254
From time immemorial,

709
01:01:54,337 --> 01:01:58,925
his people had worshiped a balance
between nature's male deities

710
01:01:59,009 --> 01:02:02,512
and the goddess or sacred feminine.

711
01:02:03,305 --> 01:02:06,850
But a growing religious turmoil
was gripping Rome.

712
01:02:07,517 --> 01:02:09,519
Three centuries earlier,

713
01:02:09,603 --> 01:02:12,397
a young Jew named Jesus had come along,

714
01:02:12,480 --> 01:02:14,983
preaching love and a single God.

715
01:02:15,275 --> 01:02:18,069
Centuries after his crucifixion,

716
01:02:18,862 --> 01:02:21,197
Christ's followers had grown exponentially

717
01:02:21,281 --> 01:02:24,367
and had started a religious war
against the pagans.

718
01:02:29,497 --> 01:02:32,876
Or did the pagans commence war
against the Christians?

719
01:02:33,543 --> 01:02:36,755
Leigh, we can't be sure who began
the atrocities in that period.

720
01:02:36,838 --> 01:02:40,050
But we can at least agree
that the conflict grew to such proportions

721
01:02:40,133 --> 01:02:41,801
that it threatened to tear Rome in two.

722
01:02:42,802 --> 01:02:46,264
So Constantine may have been
a lifelong pagan,

723
01:02:46,348 --> 01:02:48,058
but he was also a pragmatist.

724
01:02:48,141 --> 01:02:50,644
And in 325 Anno Domini,

725
01:02:50,727 --> 01:02:55,941
he decided to unify Rome
under a single religion, Christianity.

726
01:02:56,024 --> 01:02:59,861
Christianity was on the rise.
He didn't want his empire torn apart.

727
01:03:00,403 --> 01:03:03,490
And to strengthen
this new Christian tradition,

728
01:03:03,573 --> 01:03:06,242
Constantine held
a famous ecumenical gathering

729
01:03:06,326 --> 01:03:08,870
known as the Council of Nicaea.

730
01:03:09,371 --> 01:03:10,956
And at this council,

731
01:03:11,039 --> 01:03:15,794
the many sects of Christianity
debated and voted on, well,

732
01:03:15,877 --> 01:03:20,131
everything, from the acceptance
and rejection of specific gospels

733
01:03:20,215 --> 01:03:21,758
to the date for Easter

734
01:03:21,841 --> 01:03:24,803
to the administering of the sacraments,
and of course,

735
01:03:24,886 --> 01:03:27,055
the immortality of Jesus.

736
01:03:27,764 --> 01:03:29,015
I don't follow.

737
01:03:29,432 --> 01:03:32,310
Well, ma chère, until
that moment in history,

738
01:03:32,394 --> 01:03:37,232
Jesus was viewed by many
of his followers as a mighty prophet,

739
01:03:37,315 --> 01:03:41,152
as a great and powerful man,
but a man nevertheless.

740
01:03:41,569 --> 01:03:43,405
A mortal man.

741
01:03:43,613 --> 01:03:44,906
Not the Son of God?

742
01:03:44,990 --> 01:03:47,617
Not even his nephew twice removed.

743
01:03:47,701 --> 01:03:51,538
Constantine did not create Jesus' divinity.

744
01:03:51,621 --> 01:03:55,583
He simply sanctioned
an already widely held idea.

745
01:03:55,667 --> 01:03:57,502
- Semantics.
- No, it's not semantics.

746
01:03:57,585 --> 01:04:00,755
You're interpreting facts
to support your own conclusions.

747
01:04:00,839 --> 01:04:05,593
Fact. For many Christians, Jesus was
mortal one day and divine the next.

748
01:04:05,677 --> 01:04:07,679
For some Christians,
his divinity was enhanced.

749
01:04:07,762 --> 01:04:10,306
Absurd. There was even a formal
announcement of his promotion.

750
01:04:10,390 --> 01:04:12,350
They couldn't even agree
on the Nicene Creed!

751
01:04:12,434 --> 01:04:15,854
Excuse me. "Who is God, who is man?"

752
01:04:20,567 --> 01:04:23,445
How many have been murdered
over this question?

753
01:04:24,279 --> 01:04:27,323
As long as there has been a one true God,

754
01:04:27,407 --> 01:04:29,576
there has been killing in his name.

755
01:04:38,126 --> 01:04:40,754
Now let me show you the Grail.

756
01:04:43,298 --> 01:04:46,468
I trust you recognize The Last Supper,

757
01:04:46,551 --> 01:04:50,555
the great fresco by Leonardo da Vinci.

758
01:04:52,932 --> 01:04:55,685
Now, my dear, if you would close your eyes.

759
01:04:55,769 --> 01:04:57,604
Leigh, save us the parlor tricks.

760
01:04:58,188 --> 01:05:00,523
You asked for my help, I recall.

761
01:05:00,607 --> 01:05:03,234
Allow an old man his indulgences.

762
01:05:07,655 --> 01:05:11,076
Now, mademoiselle, where is Jesus sitting?

763
01:05:11,659 --> 01:05:13,495
- In the middle.
- Good.

764
01:05:13,578 --> 01:05:16,414
He and his disciples are breaking bread.

765
01:05:16,623 --> 01:05:19,292
And what drink?

766
01:05:19,375 --> 01:05:21,377
Wine. They drank wine.

767
01:05:21,461 --> 01:05:23,880
Splendid. And one final question.

768
01:05:23,963 --> 01:05:26,633
How many wineglasses are
there on the table?

769
01:05:28,343 --> 01:05:30,386
One? The Holy Grail?

770
01:05:30,470 --> 01:05:31,471
Open your eyes.

771
01:05:34,432 --> 01:05:36,059
No single cup.

772
01:05:36,643 --> 01:05:37,852
No chalice.

773
01:05:38,061 --> 01:05:40,814
Well, that's a bit strange, isn't it?

